1 B. Reimbursement is limited to $5,000 per eligible law enforcement canine for the life
2 of the canine, subject to available appropriations and submittal of documentation
3 required under subsections 3 and 4. An agency head may, at the agency head's sole
4 discretion, provide additional reimbursement from the agency's appropriated budget,
5 including, but not limited to, a designated subfund or line-item allocation. There is no
6 limit on the amount a law enforcement agency may reimburse from its own funds.
7 3. Eligibility. To qualify for reimbursement under this section:
8 A. A canine must be a retired law enforcement canine;
9 B. The applicant must reside in the State;
10 C. The canine may not be in active service with any state or local law enforcement
11 agency; and
12 D. A completed application must be submitted to the Department of Public Safety that
13 includes:
14 (1) A diagnosis by a veterinarian licensed in accordance with Title 32, section
15 4860; and
16 (2) Proof of veterinary expenses incurred.
17 4. Funding sources. The fund consists of:
18 A. Appropriations and allocations from the Legislature;
19 B. Contributions from private sources, including donations, grants and endowments;
20 and
21 C. Fines or fees collected and allocated by the Legislature.
22 If appropriations and allocations from the Legislature are insufficient, a law enforcement
23 agency may use funds from its appropriated budget, including agency-specific subfunds or
24 designated line-item allocations, to reimburse veterinary expenses for a retired law
25 enforcement canine that served in that agency. Such a reimbursement is at the sole
26 discretion of the agency head.
27 5. Rulemaking. The Commissioner of Public Safety shall adopt rules to implement
28 this section. The rules must:
29 A. Establish reimbursement guidelines;
30 B. Establish application procedures;
31 C. Ensure equitable distribution of funds; and
32 D. Identify procedures for maintaining records of disbursements.
33 Rules adopted pursuant to this subsection are routine technical rules as defined in Title 5,
34 chapter 375, subchapter 2-A.
35 SUMMARY
3366 This bill establishes the Retired Law Enforcement K-9 Health Care Fund, administered
3377 by the Department of Public Safety, to reimburse up to $5,000 for veterinary expenses for
3388 eligible retired law enforcement canines who served on a state law enforcement agency.
3399 To be eligible, canines must have served a minimum of 5 years in active law enforcement
